question.question_text: Who will be the first to leave the Trump Cabinet?
question.resolution_criteria:
This question will resolve as the first member of the Cabinet of Donald Trump to leave (by quitting, being fired, or being impeached), according to [credible sources](https://www.metaculus.com/faq/#definitions). If a cabinet member not listed here is the first to leave, this question will resolve as **Other Cabinet Member**.

If no cabinet member leaves before January 1, 2029, this question will be **annulled**.

question.background_info:
The composition and stability of a presidential cabinet offer a window into an administration’s cohesion and policy direction. Cabinet reshuffling can [influence public perception and signal a shift in an administrations priorities](https://sites.google.com/site/thepoliticsteacherorg/the-us-cabinet "The US Cabinet"). Incumbent presidents in particular expect high levels of turnover among top political appointees, especially at the start of a second term. Data shows that an average of [46% of top Senate-confirmed officials leave their jobs](https://presidentialtransition.org/transition-planning-second-term-administrations/ "Transition planning is crucial for second-term administrations") within the first six months of second terms. Worth noting, although Donald Trump is in his second term, he was not the incumbent president going into the 2024 election

With Donald Trump’s second term underway as of March 2025, speculation abounds over which cabinet member might be the first to depart—whether due to scandal, policy clashes, or external pressures. This question, featuring key cabinet members like Howard Lutnick (Commerce), Linda McMahon (Education), Marco Rubio (State), Susie Wiles (White House Chief of Staff), reflects both individual vulnerabilities (e.g., role demands) and broader political dynamics. Early exits can signal Trump’s leadership style, loyalty tests, or unexpected crises, making this a meaningful gauge of his administration’s trajectory.
